Guidelines for Private Health Practice and Facility Licensing in Botswana
These guidelines, effective May 17, 2024, are designed to ensure quality private health services in Botswana, aligning with Sustainable Development Goal 3 (good health and well-being by 2030) and Vision 2036 (Human social development, health, and wellness). They also incorporate other relevant legislation and policies, including the Botswana Health Professions Act, the Private Hospitals and Nursing Homes Act, the Medicines and Related Substances Act, and the Public Health Act.
The Private Practice and Licensing Committee facilitates licensing under the Botswana Health Professions Act, while the Director of Health Services is responsible for licensing private practitioners. The Minister of Health grants permission for hospitals, nursing homes, rehabilitation centers, and larger facilities.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
General Licensing Process Flow
The licensing process involves several key stages, applicable to various categories of practitioners and facilities:
1.
Application Submission [18a]:
◦
Applicants must submit their application in the prescribed format, including all stipulated requirements for their specific category [18a].
◦
The application will be processed by the Private Practice Licensing Office under the Director of Health Services [18b].
2.
Committee Review and Permission to Establish [18b, 18c]:
◦
Applications are presented to the Private Practice and Licensing Committee for adjudication, discussion, and regulation issues [15e, 18b]. The Committee meets monthly or as deemed necessary by the Director to assess applications [15f].
◦
The Committee has the authority to approve, grant, decline, deny, or defer applications in accordance with the guidelines [15e].
◦
A successful applicant will first be granted permission to establish private practice in a specific town, village, or city [18c].
◦
Important Note: This permission to establish is not synonymous with a private practice licence nor does it signify commencement of service [18c]. It grants the applicant time to set up:
▪
One (1) year for individual private practices [18c].
▪
Five (5) years for Hospitals, Nursing Homes, Emergency Medical Services (EMS), and other facilities [18c].
3.
Application for Inspection [19d]:
◦
Once the applicant is ready and the practice is set up, they must apply for an inspection of their services with the Department of Health Inspectorate [19d].
4.
Inspection and Licence Issuance [19e, 19f]:
◦
Upon receiving the inspection request, the inspection will be carried out, and a report will be made available within 21 days [19e].
◦
A private practice licence shall be issued after a satisfactory report has been provided by the Health Inspectorate [19f]. An inspection template is provided as a guiding tool [19f].
◦
Licence holders are not permitted to rent out their practice licences [19g].

